📄 Confluence Page: CRM to Olympus – HTTP to HTTPS Migration Guide

⸻

🧭 1. Objective

The objective of this document is to provide a step-by-step guide to migrate applications from HTTP to HTTPS based on the implementation done for:

CRM to Olympus Application

This guide can be used by other teams for similar HTTPS migrations.

⸻

🏗️ 2. Existing Architecture (Before Change)

Client → Apigee → VIP URL (HTTP) → Application
	•	Communication between components was over HTTP
	•	No SSL/TLS encryption
	•	Traffic was not secured
	•	No certificate validation involved

⸻

🔐 3. Target Architecture (After Change)

Client → Apigee → VIP URL → WIP URL → Application (HTTPS)
	•	HTTPS enabled between all components
	•	Traffic is encrypted using SSL/TLS
	•	WIP URL introduced for internal routing
	•	Certificates used for secure communication

⸻

📜 4. Certificate Setup (Actual Implementation Followed)

Instead of using CMP-issued certificates directly, the following approach was used:
	•	Downloaded CA certificates from Citi PKI Portal (Production CA → Java JKS format)
	•	Generated a self-signed certificate with:
	•	CN = WIP URL
	•	Validity = 1 year
	•	Imported Root CA and Intermediate CA into JKS keystore
	•	Verified keystore for certificate chain and private key
	•	Deployed JKS file to server
	•	Configured application to use SSL with keystore

⸻

⚙️ 5. Application Changes

Following changes were made in the application:
	•	Enabled HTTPS support in Spring Boot configuration
	•	Configured keystore path, password, and alias
	•	Updated WebClient to call HTTPS endpoints
	•	Introduced SSL bypass (temporary) using insecure trust manager
	•	Added routing logic to replicate calls to secondary endpoint

Replication logic conditions:
	•	Environment = PROD or COB
	•	Primary call is successful
	•	Route flag is false

⸻

🔁 6. SSL Handling (Important)

Due to certificate trust issues, SSL validation was bypassed temporarily in code.

Reason:
	•	Self-signed certificate was not trusted by default
	•	To avoid handshake failures during migration

⚠️ Note: This is not recommended for long-term production usage.

⸻

🚀 7. Deployment Steps
	•	Built application using Maven with SSL flags enabled
	•	Fixed Jenkins pipeline issues related to artifact copy
	•	Ensured correct target and install directory structure
	•	Deployed application using UDeploy
	•	Restarted application/pods after deployment

⸻

🧪 8. Validation Steps
	•	Verified HTTPS endpoint using curl command
	•	Checked SSL handshake and certificate details
	•	Validated application logs for successful requests
	•	Ensured replication to secondary endpoint is working
	•	Confirmed no runtime SSL errors

⸻

⚠️ 9. Issues Faced
	•	SSL error: “Untrusted Root Certificate”
	•	Cause: Self-signed certificate not trusted
	•	Jenkins failure due to incorrect file path in copy stage
	•	SSL handshake failures before bypass implementation

⸻

🛠️ 10. Fixes Applied
	•	Imported CA certificates into keystore
	•	Used insecure trust manager to bypass SSL validation
	•	Corrected Jenkins copy paths and ensured build artifacts exist
	•	Validated certificate setup using curl and openssl

⸻

📌 11. Key Learnings
	•	Always validate certificate chain before deployment
	•	Ensure CN matches WIP/VIP URL
	•	Avoid wildcard paths in Jenkins scripts
	•	SSL bypass should only be temporary
	•	Proper CA-signed certificates are required for production

⸻

✅ 12. Recommended Approach for Future
	•	Use CMP-issued certificates signed by Citi CA
	•	Avoid self-signed certificates in production
	•	Remove SSL bypass logic
	•	Ensure full certificate trust chain
	•	Perform proper SSL validation

⸻

📊 13. Summary
	•	HTTP to HTTPS migration completed successfully
	•	Secure communication established
	•	Temporary SSL bypass used for stability
	•	Deployment pipeline issues resolved
	•	Solution ready for reuse by other teams

⸻

📘 14. Conclusion

The CRM to Olympus application was successfully migrated from HTTP to HTTPS with minimal impact. The implementation included certificate setup, application updates, and deployment fixes.

This document can be used as a standard reference for similar migrations across teams.
